## 11. GLOSSARY

| Term | Definition |
|------|-----------|
| **Void cuboid** | 3D box showing only the 6 outer face textures extracted from video frame edges through time. Fast, low memory. |
| **Filled cuboid** | 3D box with ALL interior pixels captured (full frame per slice). Slow, high disk usage. Each interior slice is saved as a separate image. |
| **Slit-scan / Slice** | Classic technique: extract a thin strip of pixels from each video frame. Concatenated strips form a 2D temporal image. Time flows along one axis. |
| **Rings / Cone** | Dendrochronology-inspired 2D visualization. Center = first frame's center pixel. Concentric rings expand outward, each ring = one frame's pixels at increasing radius. Like tree rings. |
| **Slit-tear** | Multiple user-drawn freeform lines sampled through time (from Tang et al.). Produces a composite 2D image where each band corresponds to one drawn line. Can track different frame regions simultaneously. |
| **Cylinder** | Like cuboid but with a circular mask. The perimeter pixels through time form the cylinder surface texture. |
| **Sedimentation rate / Sampling rate** | Use every Nth frame (N=1 means all frames). Reduces memory and processing time proportionally. Like geological sedimentation — sampling layers rather than examining every grain. |
| **Chroma key** | Making a selected color transparent. Like green screen in film. Tolerance controls how similar a pixel must be. Fade creates smooth edges. |
| **Shot detection** | Automatic identification of cuts/transitions in video. Using PySceneDetect's ContentDetector which measures frame-to-frame difference. |
| **Mask** | The region of the video frame selected for pixel extraction. Shape depends on mode: rectangle (cuboid), circle (cylinder), line (slice), freeform (slit-tear). Displayed as a red overlay on the frame preview. |
| **Face images / textures** | The 6 images (front, back, top, bottom, left, right) that map onto the 6 faces of a cuboid or the caps/surface of a cylinder. |
| **Orthogonal** | Two slices perpendicular to each other forming a cross shape in 3D space. |
| **Unfold / Printable** | A 2D layout of a 3D object's faces arranged for cutting, folding, and gluing into a physical paper model. Standard cross pattern for cubes. |

